  footnotes: []
english:
  title: The River
  author: Park In-beom
  language: eng
  text: |-
    At dusk on the reedy shore, I moor my magnolia boat
    In the cold dew, insects cry along the autumn bank
    Where the tide has fallen, sand vanishes from ancient shallows
    As the sun sinks, even the trees on the barren island seem to grieve
    Wind drives a flock of geese across the river's expanse
    While moonlight alone escorts my solitary boat toward the distant sky
    Together we've endured this separation year after year, grown old in exile
    Each time I speak of my heart's burden, tears only flow
  footnotes:
    - The 'magnolia boat' suggests a vessel of modest beauty, emphasizing the speaker's lonely journey
    - The imagery of autumn—insects, cold dew, barren islands—establishes a melancholic atmosphere of separation and exile
    - The contrast between the flock of geese and the solitary boat underscores the speaker's isolation despite being part of a larger world
